texts.textentryhtml: As exemplified by this work, Salle’s compositions are characterized by a collage aesthetic, wherein disparate images are excised from their original contexts and layered together to expressive ends. In 1976, following his graduation from the California Institute of the Arts, the artist moved from Los Angeles to New York, where he took a job in a publishing house and began collecting the magazines that would form a visual archive of subjects for his paintings and prints. Salle relished the opportunity to mix figures from historical artistic masterpieces with cartoon figures and motifs from commercial media. The central figures in this work have been inverted on the vertical page such that, when seen from a distance, they might at first appear to be the layered, gestural skeins of color of an Abstract Expressionist canvas. Upon closer inspection one recognizes traditional symbols of medicine, characters from pulp fiction, and nudes.
